Yes ‚Äî you can easily search for a word or phrase across many PDFs in a folder. Here are the simplest methods depending on whether you use Windows, Mac, or command-line tools.

‚úÖ 1. Windows: Search inside all PDFs
Method A: Built-in Windows Search

Windows can search inside PDFs if you have a PDF reader installed (Adobe Reader, Foxit, etc.).

Open the folder containing your PDFs.

In the top-right search box, type:

content:"your word here"


Example:

content:"invoice"


Windows will list only PDFs that contain that word.

Method B: Adobe Acrobat (Reader or Pro)

Open Adobe Acrobat.

Press Ctrl + Shift + F ‚Üí opens Advanced Search.

Choose "All PDF Documents in" ‚Üí browse and select your folder.

Type the word you want to find.

Acrobat will show all PDFs containing that word and even the page numbers.

This is the best method.

‚úÖ 2. Mac (macOS): Spotlight Finder Search

Open Finder ‚Üí go to the folder with PDFs.

In the search box type the word.

Click "Name matches" and change to "Contents".

Choose Search: This Folder.

Finder will show PDFs containing that word.

‚úÖ 3. Using Command-Line (Windows/Linux/Mac)

If you prefer a script:

Python script (simple and free)
import PyPDF2
import os

folder = "/path/to/your/pdf/folder"
search_word = "your_word_here"

for file in os.listdir(folder):
    if file.endswith(".pdf"):
        path = os.path.join(folder, file)
        try:
            with open(path, "rb") as f:
                reader = PyPDF2.PdfReader(f)
                for page in reader.pages:
                    text = page.extract_text() or ""
                    if search_word.lower() in text.lower():
                        print("Found in:", file)
                        break
        except:
            pass


Run it ‚Üí it prints all PDFs containing the word.

